\begin_layout Standard
As these rep-tiles are polygons, rigorous mathematical descriptions of each
 are easily within reach.
 A square with given side length defines that shape.
 The three side lengths of a triangle define its shape.
 The height of the L-shape with an appropriate accompanying name (though
 I'm not sure there is one) would suffice to describe the last one.
 In the absence of a good name, perhaps the height with a description such
 as a square with one quadrant missing will do as a complete description.
 Linear algebra provides language to do better!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After building a larger replica of a rep-tile, one can switch perspecives
 and look at the construction as a dissection of the larger rep-tile.
 From this viewpoint, rep-tiles are tiles that tessellate the plane and
 admit a dissection into finitely many similar copies.
 All the figures of the previous diagram can be seen from this vantage.
 The larger square is made up of four smaller squares.
 The triangle is broken up into four similar triangles.
 The L-shape is likewise divided into four smaller copies of itself.
\end_layout

